[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is a strong third recipe for the Anomaly Detection chapter and the densest payment-integrity writing in the cookbook to date. The Thursday-afternoon vignette (a payment integrity analyst at a regional payer staring at 142,000 claims across 18,000 billing providers, the dermatology practice billing 97110 on eighty-four claims when most dermatologists bill it zero times a year, the internist whose codes-per-visit jumped from two to five over two months, the urgent care whose E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM distribution slid from a bell curve at 99213 to a distribution leaning on 99214 and 99215, the team's investigation capacity of forty cases per month against a 1% anomaly rate that produces 180 candidates) lands the operational reality in three paragraphs. The five concrete behavioral-drift examples (CCM expansion, PT four-code regimen, HCPCS G0299 unit-rounding at exactly four units, modifier 59 at 42% of claims, lab CPT-mix shift with 18% per-claim dollar increase) are the kind of dense-and-specific framing that signals a writer who has been in payment integrity work, and each one maps to a real billing scenario any payment integrity director would recognize. The three-flavors-of-anomaly framing (point, contextual, collective) is the right teaching anchor and recurs through the rest of the recipe; the explicit observation that "a billing anomaly detector isn't really a 'score the incoming claim' system. It's a 'continuously model each provider's behavior and flag the changes' system" is the kind of architectural reframe that distinguishes this recipe from generic anomaly-detection writing. The three-comparison-axes section (self vs. peer vs. expected-given-patient-mix) is publication-ready voice on the design decisions most teams get wrong. The feature-families taxonomy is correctly ordered by signal-to-effort ratio with the right closing observation that "Most teams build the self-comparison and peer-comparison features first and get 80% of the value." The statistical-methods progression (z-scores → control charts/CUSUM → Isolation Forest → matrix factorization → gradient boosting → embeddings) is the right pedagogical order, and the recipe correctly says "A reasonable progression: start with z-scores and CUSUM. Add Isolation Forest once you've seen enough data to tune thresholds." The peer-group subsection, the labeling-problem subsection (with the specific call-out that "Most investigations don't close with a clean 'fraud' or 'not fraud' label"), and the fairness/legitimacy/harassment-of-legitimate-variation subsection are all hard-won-experience teaching that a working payment integrity director would write. The four-stage architecture (provider-period aggregator → peer-group assembler → anomaly scoring → case assembly + prioritization, plus feedback loop) is the architecturally correct factoring and the diagram and walkthrough align with each other (no diagram-vs-walkthrough drift, unlike Recipe 3.1). The Honest Take is publication-ready: the seven lessons (feature engineering matters more than the model, peer group definition is the most consequential design decision, the operational cost of false positives is worse than you think, the narrative summary is surprisingly important, the Isolation Forest catches things z-scores don't, the don't-build-supervised-first lesson, the don't-let-the-system-drive-toward-maximize-cases trap) land the right teaching priorities and end with the right operational metric framing ("dollars recovered per analyst hour" or "investigations-closed-with-action per case created," not volume).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mStyle hygiene is clean. Zero em dashes (direct U+2014 character check: zero matches). Zero en dashes in prose (the 8 detected en dash matches are inside ASCII art box-drawing characters in the architecture diagram, not in narrative text), an even cleaner posture than Recipes 3.1 and 3.2. No marketing language ("leverage," "seamless," "unlock," "transform," "empower," "revolutionize" all absent). No documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly: the conceptual sections (Problem, Technology, General Architecture Pattern) are vendor-neutral and a reader on GCP or Azure could substitute their cloud's primitives without rewriting any of the teaching; AWS service names enter at the AWS Implementation section and stay there. HTML-comment TODOs (3 total) are all forward-placeholder for industry-source citation or aws-samples repository verification, which is the chapter-wide settled posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe most consequential cluster of findings is around domain accuracy in the E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM feature engineering and the recurring trigger-idempotency pattern. The 2021 CMS/AMA E/M documentation overhaul deleted CPT 99201, restructured documentation requirements for 99202-99215, and produced a structural break in historical E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM distributions that affected nearly every outpatient provider in the United States simultaneously. The 2023 inpatient/observation E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM changes (99221-99239 and the 99217-99220 / 99224-99226 / 99231-99239 reorganization) produced a similar structural break for inpatient codes. The recipe presents the E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM-distribution-shift example ("A provider whose E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM distribution shifts from centered-on-99213 to centered-on-99214") as the canonical upcoding pattern without acknowledging that a population-wide shift in this exact direction occurred legitimately around 2021-01-01 because the documentation rules changed. The recipe's "Where it struggles" section addresses payer-specific policy changes ("When the payer changes a policy ... provider billing adjusts. The adjustments will look like anomalies until the baselines catch up. Pause or dampen the signals during known policy rollouts") but doesn't extend this discipline to industry-wide CMS/AMA coding changes. The pseudocode's E[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mM level distribution treats levels 1 through 5 as a stable five-bucket categorical ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m"level_1": ..., "level_2": ..., ..., "level_5": ...[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m); for new-patient codes, level 1 (99201) does not exist post-2021 and the bucket should not appear in current-period feature vectors. The Python companion's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mEM_CODES[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m dictionary (per the existing code review at [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mreviews/chapter03.03-code-review.md[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m Finding 5) explicitly includes 99201, which carries the bug forward into runnable code.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mSeveral MEDIUM findings cluster on architectural completeness, the recurring trigger-idempotency pattern, and PHI/fairness governance: outcome-event idempotency at the EventBridge → outcome-joiner Lambda path is not modeled (recurring across Recipes 2.4-2.10, 3.1, 3.2 and now 3.3); no DLQ or poison-message handling for the case-assembly, scoring, or outcome-joiner Lambdas; the SHAP-explanation pseudocode call ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mtop_contributors: shap_explain(isolation_forest, record, top_k = 5)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m) misrepresents how SHAP applies to Isolation Forest (TreeSHAP doesn't directly support IF; Kernel SHAP works but is computationally expensive; common production patterns use path-length attribution or feature-mean deviations as a proxy); SNS analyst-notification payload PHI minimization is not explicit (the chapter-3-settled "case-id-only" convention from Recipe 3.1 is implied but not stated); subgroup data governance for fairness monitoring is acknowledged in prose ("Coordinate with provider-network operations on what attributes are available") but the architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding are not specified.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    20[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    21[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mLOW findings are editorial and operational polish: VPC endpoint precision (CloudWatch monitoring vs Logs, EventBridge events vs Scheduler, SageMaker api/runtime/featurestore-runtime distinction, Glue, Step Functions, SNS); sample case-id timestamps use a future date (CASE-2026-05-000487) that will age awkwardly post-publication; the narrative-summary "or use an LLM if you have a HIPAA-eligible LLM pipeline" note glosses over the BAA discipline that Chapter 2 settled; forward-reference inconsistency between "Recipe 5.x (entity resolution)" in the walkthrough and "Recipe 5.2 (Provider Entity Resolution)" in Related Recipes; HTML-comment TODOs for industry-figure verification.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    22[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    23[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mPriority breakdown: 0 CRITICAL, 1 HIGH, 6 MEDIUM, 6 LOW.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    24[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe risk profile is similar to Recipe 3.1 (no LLM in the core path, no clinical-recommendation surface, no FDA medical-device exposure) with the same financial-and-operational stakes (provider relationship damage from false positives, recoverable-dollar leakage from false negatives) rather than patient harm. The fairness surface area is meaningful but smaller than Recipe 3.2: provider-level statistical discrimination is real (the recipe correctly addresses it in the "harassment of legitimate variation" subsection) but the operational response to a flag is investigation-and-conversation rather than service-restriction, which the recipe correctly frames as "a prompt for a conversation with the provider, not an accusation."[K
