[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    48[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Step 4 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140massemble_cases[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, the SNS publish at the end ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mSNS.Publish(topic = ANALYST_NOTIFICATION_TOPIC, message = { case_id, provider_id, severity, routing, exposure })[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m); Why-These-Services Amazon SNS paragraph; Prerequisites IAM row.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    49[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The pseudocode's SNS message payload includes [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mprovider_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mseverity[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrouting[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mexposure[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (in addition to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcase_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m). Provider IDs are PHI-adjacent (a provider NPI plus a date range plus a patient population is re-identifying in combination), and dollar exposure values inside an SNS notification create an additional PHI-adjacent surface that traverses SNS infrastructure, downstream subscribers (email, Slack via webhook, mobile push), and any logs those subscribers generate. Recipe 3.1's expert review settled the chapter discipline on this point: "The message carries the case id only; the analyst UI fetches the full record by id so the notification channel never carries PHI." Recipe 3.3 doesn't follow that convention in either prose or pseudocode, and the Python companion (per the existing code review's healthcare-specific section) is forced to make the call independently. The risk is low but the inconsistency teaches readers a different convention than Recipes 3.1 and 3.2 did, and SNS subscriber endpoints (especially email/SMS/Slack via downstream integrations) are exactly the surface where lock-screen previews and shared-device exposure produce real PHI leakage.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    50[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Update the Step 4 pseudocode to publish only [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcase_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and a coarse routing tier (e.g., "high-severity" / "clinical-review") in the SNS payload, with the comment: "The message carries the case id and routing tier only; the analyst UI fetches the full case record (including provider_id, signals, evidence claims, exposure) by id so the notification channel never carries PHI or PHI-adjacent identifiers." Add a one-line note to the Why-These-Services paragraph for SNS that names this convention. Same chapter-3-settled minimum-PHI-in-notification pattern as Recipe 3.1.[K
