[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    74[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Step 5 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_investigation_outcome[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (writes to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcase-registry[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlabels-parquet[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m); Prerequisites Encryption row; Retention row.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    75[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Investigation outcomes (disposition, resolution notes, dollars recovered, SIU referral status) are the source-of-truth records for any downstream provider grievance, regulatory inquiry, SIU continuation, or law enforcement referral. The recipe writes them to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcase-registry[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (DynamoDB, mutable per-item) and to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlabels-parquet[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (S3, mutable unless explicit Object Lock is applied). DynamoDB items are mutable: the table owner can update or delete the item and the change is reversible only via point-in-time recovery within the PITR window (35 days). For a record that may be subpoenaed in a fraud investigation 2-7 years after creation (the multi-regime retention horizon), the case-registry default offering is weaker than the audit posture warrants. Same finding shape as Recipe 3.1 S2 (auto-suspension records).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    76[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    77[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mTwo production patterns are common: (a) write a parallel decision record to S3 with Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode at the time the outcome is captured (the recipe specifies S3 for [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlabels-parquet[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m but does not specify Object Lock), or (b) write decision records to Amazon QLDB for cryptographic verification of decision history. The recipe's CloudTrail data-events discipline addresses the read-trail concern but not the write-immutability concern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    78[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add to the Encryption row or to a new Auditability row in Prerequisites: "Investigation outcome records and disposition decisions are subject to provider grievance, regulatory inquiry, and SIU/law-enforcement subpoena. Configure S3 Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode on the [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlabels-parquet[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m bucket in production (GOVERNANCE mode in dev so test data can be cleaned up). Optionally write a parallel decision-record log to Amazon QLDB if cryptographic verification of decision history is required by your organization's compliance posture." Add a one-line mention in "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" under the existing "Data retention is complicated" bullet.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    79[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    80[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m###[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mArchitecture Expert Review[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    81[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    82[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mWhat's Done Well[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    83[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    84[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe four-stage pipeline (provider-period aggregator → peer-group assembler → anomaly scoring → case assembly + prioritization, plus a feedback loop through investigation outcomes back to retraining) is the architecturally correct factoring for this problem class. The decision to make the unit of analysis the provider-period (not the individual claim) is the architectural reframe most first-time builders miss, and the recipe is explicit about it ("a billing anomaly detector isn't really a 'score the incoming claim' system. It's a 'continuously model each provider's behavior and flag the changes' system. The unit of analysis is typically the provider-month or provider-week, not the individual claim").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    85[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Three-axis comparison framing (self vs. peer vs. expected-given-patient-mix) is the right factoring, and the recipe correctly identifies that "Most mature systems run all three comparisons in parallel and combine the signals."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    86[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Three signal families (peer z-scores, self-history CUSUM, multivariate Isolation Forest) are kept architecturally separate through the pipeline ("Each signal is kept separately rather than aggregated into a single score prematurely, so the case assembly layer can explain which signal fired"). This is the right pedagogical posture for a system that needs to explain itself to analysts.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    87[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The leave-one-out discipline for peer group statistics is named explicitly with the right operational framing: "if you leave them in, you're comparing them to themselves (and if they're an extreme outlier, they're pulling the group statistic toward themselves). Leave-one-out z-scores fix this. It sounds fiddly. It matters more than you'd think when you have specialties with fewer than 100 providers." This is the kind of detail-level teaching the cookbook is built on.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    88[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Case assembly as a first-class architectural step ("This is the step most first-time builders under-invest in. The raw output of the scoring layer is a pile of signals (tens of thousands per period). The operations team can work tens of cases per analyst per month") is the operationally correct framing. Most generic anomaly-detection writeups skip this and produce systems that fire signals into a queue analysts can't process.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    89[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The peer-group fallback hierarchy (specialty + region + setting → specialty + region → specialty) with the minimum-group-size guard is the right configuration-driven approach, and the recipe correctly says "Hierarchical peer groups work well: run the comparison at multiple levels (specialty, specialty+region, specialty+region+setting) and use whichever has enough comparators."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    90[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Step Functions for monthly orchestration is correctly framed and EventBridge Scheduler is correctly used for the cadence trigger; the recipe is explicit that MWAA is a viable alternative ("Some payment integrity teams already run Airflow for their data engineering work. Stepping into Step Functions adds an operational surface; MWAA fits into an existing tool. Functionally equivalent for this pipeline; pick whichever matches your team's existing operational posture"). This is a vendor-neutral reframe that respects existing operational tooling.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    91[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The labeling-problem subsection is unusually disciplined: "Most investigations don't close with a clean 'fraud' or 'not fraud' label," "Label lag is enormous. Investigations can take 6-18 months from flag to resolution," "Self-confirming labels are a big risk," "False negatives are often never discovered." Each is a hard-won-experience point that a working ML director would say.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    92[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section is dense and architecturally substantive: provider entity resolution, peer group tuning, case deduplication across periods, analyst tooling and workflow, legal and regulatory review, provider communication protocols, explainability for the analyst, subgroup fairness monitoring, data retention, incident response when a flag is wrong, model and data drift monitoring, cost of investigation per case. Twelve substantive bullets each tied to a real production concern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    93[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Cost estimate is defensible and correctly framed against the recovered value: "Total infrastructure: typically $200-800/month. Compare to recovery: if the program prevents even 0.25% of fraudulent or erroneous payments on a $500M annual spend, that's $1.25M recovered against a $10K/year infrastructure cost." The HTML-comment TODO acknowledging that the recovery ratio should be cited from a published payer case study before publication is the right discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    94[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Implementation-time tiers (6-10 weeks Basic, 4-7 months Production-ready, 6-12 months beyond for Variations) are realistic and resist optimism bias.[K
