[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    194[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The pseudocode's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mshap_explain(isolation_forest, record, top_k = 5)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m call implies a clean SHAP application that doesn't exist for Isolation Forest. SHAP's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mTreeExplainer[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m is the fast, exact explainer for tree-based models, but it's designed for gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost) and certain random forest variants where the model exposes a leaf-level prediction function. Isolation Forest is structurally different: it's an ensemble of randomly-split trees where the "prediction" is the average path length to isolation, not a leaf-level prediction. TreeSHAP doesn't directly apply.[K
