[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    288[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Thursday-afternoon vignette is publication-ready voice. "Picture a payment integrity analyst at a regional payer on a Thursday afternoon. Her dashboard shows 142,000 claims adjudicated this week across roughly 18,000 billing providers." The specificity (142,000 claims, 18,000 providers, 40 cases per analyst per month, 1% anomaly rate produces 180 candidates, 84-claim dermatology 97110 example, two-to-five codes-per-visit jump) signals a writer who has been in payment integrity work and lands the operational reality in three paragraphs.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    289[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The five behavioral-drift examples (CCM expansion, PT four-code regimen, HCPCS G0299 unit-rounding at exactly four units, modifier 59 at 42% of claims, lab CPT-mix shift with 18% per-claim dollar increase) each map to a real billing scenario any payment integrity director would recognize. The HCPCS G0299 / four-units-per-visit / "histogram that piles up on an exact time boundary" framing is the kind of operational insight that distinguishes the cookbook from generic anomaly-detection writing. CPT codes are correctly cited (97110, 97112, 97140, 97530 for PT; 99490 for CCM with the correct 20-minute non-face-to-face descriptor; G0299 correctly identified as registered nurse per 15 minutes).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    290[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The three-flavors-of-anomaly framing (point, contextual, collective) is the right teaching anchor and is concretely illustrated for each. The architectural reframe ("a billing anomaly detector isn't really a 'score the incoming claim' system. It's a 'continuously model each provider's behavior and flag the changes' system") is the kind of authoritative voice the cookbook is built on.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    291[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The three-axes-of-comparison subsection (self vs. peer vs. expected-given-patient-mix) is publication-ready voice on the design decisions most teams get wrong. The closing observation ("Most mature systems run all three comparisons in parallel and combine the signals. A provider flagged on one axis is worth noting. A provider flagged on two or three axes simultaneously is the kind of case that pays for the whole program") is the operational truth a working payment integrity director would say.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    292[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The feature-families taxonomy is correctly ordered by signal-to-effort ratio with the right closing observation that "Most teams build the self-comparison and peer-comparison features first and get 80% of the value. The case-mix-adjusted and network features are the mature-system additions."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    293[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The statistical-methods progression (z-scores → control charts/CUSUM → Isolation Forest → matrix factorization → gradient boosting → embeddings) is the right pedagogical order, and the recipe's closing posture ("A reasonable progression: start with z-scores and CUSUM. Add Isolation Forest once you've seen enough data to tune thresholds. Add supervised classification once you've got labels. Don't go to embeddings unless you've exhausted the simpler options") is the right teaching on a topic where teams tend to over-engineer.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    294[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The peer-group subsection is unusually detailed: "A too-narrow peer group (say, 'dermatologists in this ZIP code') has too few providers for stable statistics. A too-broad peer group ('all outpatient providers') averages away the specialty-specific patterns that matter. Standard practice is to define peer groups with 30-500 providers per group, tuned to the specialty density in your coverage area." The leave-one-out subtlety ("It sounds fiddly. It matters more than you'd think when you have specialties with fewer than 100 providers") is exactly the kind of detail-level teaching the cookbook is built on.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    295[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The labeling-problem subsection is hard-won-experience teaching: the "most investigations don't close with a clean fraud/not-fraud label" observation, the 6-18 month label-lag reality, the self-confirming-labels selection-bias trap, and the "false negatives are often never discovered" observation each map to a real operational concern. The mitigation framing ("periodically random-sample from unflagged providers and have them reviewed, specifically to get 'negative' and 'other-pattern' labels into the dataset") is the right operational discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    296[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The fairness/legitimacy subsection is the most substantive treatment of provider-level fairness in the cookbook. The four-bullet harm taxonomy (operational, reputational, access, statistical-discrimination) is concrete; the four-bullet mitigation list (case-mix adjustment, transparent thresholds, investigation-as-conversation, subgroup monitoring) is operationally actionable; and the closing posture ("an anomaly flag is a prompt for a conversation with the provider, not an accusation. The conversation establishes context. Most flags resolve there. The small subset that don't is where investigation effort goes") is the right reframing for a domain where the operational response to a flag has reputational consequences.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    297[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Honest Take is publication-ready. The seven lessons (feature engineering matters more than the model, peer group definition is the most consequential design decision, the operational cost of false positives is worse than you think, the narrative summary is surprisingly important, the Isolation Forest catches things z-scores don't, don't-build-supervised-first, don't-let-the-system-drive-toward-maximize-cases) land the right teaching priorities. The closing trap warning ("If you measure the system by cases generated, you incentivize lowering the thresholds and producing more noise. If you measure it by precision-weighted recovery, you incentivize fewer, better cases. The latter is what the business actually wants, and it keeps the provider relationship manageable") is the kind of operations-engineer voice that distinguishes the cookbook.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    298[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Variations and Extensions covers the right adjacent patterns at the right depth: real-time claim-level screening for high-risk codes, patient-level anomaly overlays, network analysis for coordinated patterns (with the right hand-off to Recipe 3.6), predictive model for provider risk trajectories, case-mix-adjusted expected billing, cross-payer benchmark integration (FAIR Health correctly named), provider education program integration. Each is one to two paragraphs with enough scope to start a conversation.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    299[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Zero em dashes (direct U+2014 character check: zero matches). No en dashes in prose (the 8 detected en dash matches are inside ASCII-art box-drawing characters in the architecture diagram, not in narrative text), an even cleaner posture than Recipes 3.1 and 3.2. No marketing language. No documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly.[K
